If you own commercial property, TIV is insurance jargon you’ll hear frequently but and rarely explained.

TIV stands for Total Insured Value.

It’s the TOTAL VALUE the insurance carrier is using to price, underwrite and capacity-check your property, typically based on what it would cost to rebuild today but depending on carrier may include contents or business income as well.

Why TIV matters from an insurance company fit standpoint ⬇️

Underwriters on property heavy risks generally ask early on, “what’s the TIV?” and the reason for asking is each carriers has different comfort levels based on construction type, age, protections and geography depending on that answer. 

For example a carrier may be able to do up to $10M/bldg framed without sprinklers but has capacity at $25M/bldg if sprinklered NFPA13. If your property doesn’t fit those guidelines that company is out of the mix. When TIV aligns with those carrier appetites the underwriting becomes focused on coming together for a deal.

The goal isn’t just “the right number.” It’s the right number for the right carrier.

Next time you are reviewing your property’s Statement of Values (SOV, another insurance jargon) check out your TIV.

It’s one of the biggest drivers for company appetite and which companies are interested in your property right off the bat!
